Opioid Abuse Risk and Services Provision

Kyle McCarthy and Tristan Grupp

12/15/2020

Introduction

Heroin Overdoses are an epidemic across the United States. In the United States, there are over 60,000 opioid overdose-related deaths each year. There are two approaches a city can take to minimize heroin overdose death rates. First, they can provide more significant social services for those struggling with heroin addiction. Social services include both rehab centers and addiction support centers. Rehab centers typically help those struggling to get off drugs. Addiction support centers, similar to Alcoholics Anonymous, provide a support group for those who have experienced opioid addiction. Support groups often ensure that former drug addicts do not retake heroin or other substances. Cities can also provide clean needle exchange to reduce the spread of disease from sharing needles. Secondly, cities can provide greater EMS services to prevent opioid-related deaths. An EMS team’s optimal response time when someone goes unconscious from an opioid overdose is 4-6 minutes. This short, but necessary response time, is a significant factor in preventing heroin overdose deaths where heroin overdoses pose a considerable threat. Consequently, it is essential that cities strategically place their EMS units near opioid deaths occur.

This study hones into the city of Cincinnati, where EMS and heroin overdose data is readily available. In Cincinnati, there are over 1,000 reported heroin-related EMS calls per year. However, data entry regarding heroin overdose cases seems to be inconsistent from year to year. During 2016 we look specifically at the time from June 6, 2016 - December 21, 2016, where data entry appears to be consistent. To predict risk, we utilize a geospatial risk model. In the geospatial risk model, the dependent variable is the occurrence of discrete heroin overdose events during our time frame. Predictions from the model are forecasted as the risk of an event occurring in a given area. Incorporating data such as crime, central business districts, location of pharmacies, traffic accidents, 311 data, foreclosures, and census data, we accurately predicted heroin overdose risk within Cincinnati using a geospatial risk model. Utilizing variables such as crime, census data, central business district location, traffic accidents, and foreclosures, we hypothesize that heroin overdose risk is a function of these predictive factors. In other words, as exposure to these risk factors increases, so does heroin overdoses. The goal is to borrow from the experience of places where heroin overdoses are observed and test whether that experience generalizes to sites that may be at risk for heroin overdose, even if few events are reported. The data is divided into a test set and a training set. The training set includes data from June 23, 2016, to September 12, 2016, while the test set is any event that occurred after September 12. Predictions from our heroin overdose are latent risks, meaning that the model identifies areas of risk even though heroin overdoses may not have been reported in a given region. The model is compared to the kernel density, which determines hot spots. Many cities utilize kernel density to identify hot spots in a region to decide where to allocate resources and services. The model is compared to the kernel density to test if the model is better than this ‘business as usual’ approach. Finally, the model tests for generalizability across spatial regions. Specifically, we look at Moran’s I of errors and how the model compares when accounting for different spatial processes such as poverty or race. Generalizability is essential to ensure that the model predicts with accuracy across different Cincinnati neighborhoods. Accounting for poverty and race allows us to understand if the model is underserving or overserving different demographic and socioeconomic groups. For example, if the model does not account for a specific demographic or socioeconomic neighborhood, that demographic or socioeconomic neighborhood would be underserved if the model is put into production.

Finally, and most importantly, the model’s main purpose is to identify where to locate resources, including EMS services and opioid resource centers/community support centers. To understand where EMS services should be placed, begin by selecting regions that our model has predicted to be a high risk of heroin overdoses. Secondly, we look at where the EMS delays are the longest by taking the mean of delay time in each fishnet grid cell, which is calculated by subtracting the EMS call time from EMS arrival time. According to the CDC, any response time greater than 6 minutes is considered too long. Selected areas are buffered 1 mile and vacant lots are located within the selected region. To understand where social services are needed, rehab and support services are buffered with a 2-mile radius. Any high-risk grid cell outside of those buffers is considered a high-risk, underserved region. Those grid cells are buffered 1 mile, and vacant lots are located within the recommended buffer region.

To best account for the spatial distribution of heroin overdoses, a fishnet was created. The fishnet is used to count the number of heroin overdoses in equally-sized grid cells, treating occurrences of overdoses as an event that can occur across a surface rather than summed in arbitrary boundaries such as census tracts. Here a fishnet is created, utilizing a cell size of 500 meters by 500 meters. Fishnets are utilized to aggregate the count of points to a lattice of grid cells. Fishnets are essential to represent that heroin overdose dissipates outward from hotspots, or where high counts of heroin overdoses occur.

fishnet <- 
  st_make_grid(cincinnati, cellsize = 500) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(uniqueID = rownames(.))

Here, the spatial data frame encompassing all EMS points is mutated to only account for Heroin EMS response cases. Note the use of time when altering the data set. Heroin overdoses are divided into three separate spatial data frames. The first data frame encompasses all points, which is used for visualization purposes only. The second dataset (Hero1), will be used as the test set. The third dataset (Hero2) will be used as the training set. All of the points in both the test set and the training set are aggregated into a fishnet grid. The fishnet value (countOpioid) represents the number of heroin overdose EMS calls in each fishnet grid cell. The graph shown below represents the fishnet counts of both the combined test set and training set.

Hero <- 
  df%>%
  filter(grepl("HERO", incident_type_desc)) %>%
  filter(grepl("2016", create_time_incident))%>%
  mutate(X = as.numeric(longitude_x),Y = as.numeric(latitude_x))%>%
  dplyr::select("X", "Y", "event_number")%>%
  na.omit()%>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("X", "Y"), crs = 4326, agr = "constant")%>%
  st_transform('ESRI:102323')%>%
  left_join(df, by = "event_number")

There seems to be a spike in heroin overdoses from around August to October. This demonstrates the influence of time on overdose events. Although we recognize that there may be a temporal component in the data, represented by the spike, we could not identify any temporal variables of use to plug into the model. We previously tested for the weather, day of the week, and time of day. These variables did not seem to correlate to a better model and are disregarded from this study.

The following code displays the variables and feature engineering performed. The variables utilized were pharmacy locations, collected from various online sources, traffic, public buildings, bus stops, neighborhood central business district locations, foreclosures, shootings, assaults, theft, vandalism, and burglary. Additionally, to account for spatial processes, we downloaded neighborhoods and census variables such as median household income, male population, and poverty. Many of these variables, such as traffic and bus stops, seem unrelated to heroin overdoses. The figure below this set of code helps explains why these variables are included. As depicted, downtown regions or higher populations tend to have higher counts of heroin overdoses on average than areas away from downtown. Consequently, we included traffic, central business district location, and bus stops to account for density in downtown areas. Note that CBD was also significantly feature engineered. The CBD variable represents fishnet grid cells where the fishnet grid cell centroid intersects with a central business district polygon.

The next step includes feature engineering. For these variables, the nearest neighbor function was used to calculate ‘average nearest neighbor distance’ from each heroin opioid overdose to its k nearest neighbor for each variable. For example, k is equal to five in pharmacies, meaning that the nearest neighbor function is calculating the average nearest distance to its five nearest neighbors from each pharmacy. The nearest neighbor function works because it first creates a matrix of distances from each point k to each heroin overdose. The matrix is then converted to a data frame, and a unique field is created representing each point distance. The data is then converted from wide to long and orders the data by ascending distance. Finally, the mean average distance is calculated using the summarized function and calculates the mean average neighbor distances. Note that this is not the first time feature engineering was done so far.

function(measureFrom,measureTo,k) {
  measureFrom_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureFrom)
  measureTo_Matrix <-
    as.matrix(measureTo)
  nn <-   
    get.knnx(measureTo, measureFrom, k)$nn.dist
  output <-
    as.data.frame(nn) %>%
    rownames_to_column(var = "thisPoint") %>%
    gather(points, point_distance, V1:ncol(.)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>%
    group_by(thisPoint) %>%
    summarize(pointDistance = mean(point_distance)) %>%
    arrange(as.numeric(thisPoint)) %>% 
    dplyr::select(-thisPoint) %>%
    pull()
  
  return(output)  
}

The Moran’s I value looks to see if there is spatial autocorrelation, which is when there is clustering in the data. A higher moran’s I value indicates a more significant clustering of heroin opioid EMS calls in that region. High Moran’s I values are spatially located within Cincinnati’s downtown region and west of the downtown region. Consequently, when modeling heroin overdoses, it is essential to account for regions of higher populations because that is where heroin overdoses seem to cluster. A p-value of 0.5 indicates that higher heroin overdose counts are expected under random conditions. Values of less than 0.5 are used to define significant hotspots. Hotspots are represented in yellow on map 4 in the figure below.

Correlating the variables helps determine which variables will significantly impact the model and which variables should be incorporated into the model. Generally, the higher the R squared value, the better the model. Crime variables seem to correlate well with the count of heroin overdoses, particularly the nearest neighbors of shootings, assaults, theft, and burglaries. Additionally, variables associated with downtown spatial regions such as traffic accidents, bus stops, and distance to neighborhood central business districts also seem to be strong predictors. A surprising finding is the nearest neighbor to pharmacies seem to negatively correlate to opioid overdoses, meaning heroin overdoses tend to occur closer to pharmacies. We hypothesis that pharmacies may lead to increased drug availability, leading to an increased amount of prescription drug medication in the region. Although you cannot find heroin at a pharmacy, many prescription opioid medications may lead to heroin addiction.

Additionally, each of the independent variables must be independent of one another. The second figure below depicts a correlation plot, where a value of 1 indicates the variables are positively correlated, and a value of -1 means the variables are negatively correlated. If the correlation between 2 variables is 1, or -1, only one of the variables should be included in the model. Three relationships pose a problem. Foreclosures and shootings are seemingly positively correlated. Percent Poverty and median household income seem to be negatively correlated. Finally, downtown distance and nearest neighbor to central business districts are positively correlated.

Model

In this section, the training set, Final_net1 is validated on the test set, Final_net2. Poisson regression is based on the Poisson distribution. Poisson regression assumes the response variable Y has a Poisson distribution, and assumes a linear combination of unknown parameters can model the logarithm of its expected value. Since the count of heroin overdoses in a fishnet grid represents a Poisson distribution, it makes the most sense to use poison regression to model heroin overdoses. For a given neighborhood name, in the cross-validation function, the function assigns each grid cell not in that neighborhood to the training set, fold.train, and each cell in that neighborhood to the test set, fold.test. A model is trained from the former and used to predict the latter. The process is repeated until each neighborhood has a turn acting as a hold.

ggplot(final_net, aes(x=countOpioid))+
  geom_histogram(color="darkblue", fill="lightblue")+
  labs(title = "Count of Heroin Overdoses by Fishnet", x = "Number of Overdoses", y = "Number of Fishnet Grids")

cross <- function(train, test, id, dependentVariable, indVariables) {
  
  allPredictions <- data.frame()
  cvID_list <- unique(train[[id]])
  
  for (i in cvID_list) {
    
    thisFold <- i
    cat("This hold out fold is", thisFold, "\n")
    
    fold.train <- 
      filter(train, train[[id]] != thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    fold.test  <- filter(test, test[[id]] == thisFold) %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
      dplyr::select(id, geometry, indVariables, dependentVariable)
    
    regression <-
      glm(countOpioid ~ ., family = "poisson", 
          data = fold.train %>% 
            dplyr::select(-geometry, -id))
    
    thisPrediction <- 
      mutate(fold.test, Prediction = predict(regression, fold.test, type = "response"))
    
    allPredictions <-
      rbind(allPredictions, thisPrediction)
    
  }
  return(st_sf(allPredictions))
}

In this section, the cross-validation function from the code above is performed. The functions are performed twice, once for k-fold regression and once for LOGO regression. K-fold regression partitions the data into equal sizes, which are known as folds. For a given fold, the model is trained on a subset of observations and predicted on a test. K-fold cross-validation takes the average goodness of fit across all k-folds. In contrast, in Leave Out Cross Validation (LOGO cross validation) each neighborhood takes a turn as a holdout. LOGO cross-validation can be very helpful when a specific neighborhood has distinct characteristics because that particular neighborhood has the opportunity to act as the holdout. Note once again that final-net1 is the training set and final_net2 is the test set.

Here we analyze if the model’s accuracy and generalizability. In comparing LOGO-CV to K-Fold cross-validation, K-Fold cross-validation appears to be the more slightly accurate model. The model’s accuracy seems to be high, predicting less than five errors in a given grid cell for K-Fold Cross-Validation. As depicted in the prediction maps, high-risk errors seem to locate within Downtown Cincinnati or near that region. A positive aspect of this model is that the mean average errors are randomly distributed across space. The Moran’s I value for mean average errors is approximately 0, meaning that there is very little clustering of errors across space. A clustering of values would indicate that the model does not account for a characteristic of a given region where heroin overdoses occur. Consequently, the model seems to be generalizable across space based on the Moran’s I value.

It is also essential to determine if the model does well when generalizing across different socioeconomic and demographic characteristics. This is essential because if the model is not generalizable across different demographics and socioeconomic statuses, specific demographics and socioeconomic statuses would be underserved while allocated resources to prevent heroin overdose deaths and heroin overdose addiction in Cincinnati. For demographics, we compared the mean average error for predominantly minority communities to predominately white communities. We found that the model is generalizable across a racial context. The mean average error when accounting for racial context is around .12 in predominately white neighborhoods and predominately minority neighborhoods. K-Fold validation seems to be more generalizable across spatial scales compared to LOGO-CV. When comparing communities with a 25 percent poverty rate, the model still seems to be generalizable across space to neighborhoods with less than a 25 percent poverty race. The mean error by neighborhood context is very low and close to 0 for both regions where at least 1/4 of the community is in poverty and neighborhoods where less than 1/4 of the people have poverty status. One conclusion that can be made is that K-fold validation is more accurate and generalizable than LOGO-CV validation. Therefore K-Fold Validation should be utilized over LOGO-CV.

The kernel density is a ‘business as usual’ approach. Kernel density works by centering a smooth kernel, or curve, atop each crime point such that the curve is at its highest directly over the point and the lowest at the range of a circular search radius. The density in a particular place is the sum of all the kernels that underlie it. Thus, areas with many nearby points have relatively high densities. The mean average errors are approximately the same for the first four risk categories when comparing K-Fold validation to kernel density predictions. The model presented above appears to be slightly better at predicting the highest risk categories. Although both models are similar regarding the mean average error, we still recommend that our model is put into production. When allocating resources, the model must generalize across space, so resources are most responsibly allocated. Our model has proven to generalize across space and across different race and poverty contexts.

This section analyzes where to locate EMS services. Using the original heroin data collected, we look specifically at the time difference between the dispatch time and the arrival time. According to the CDC, it is recommended that EMS services arrive in under 6 minutes for overdose cases to reduce death risk significantly. Consequently, EMS services must be fast and readily available. For this analysis, we looked at high-risk areas based on the model (> 6 overdoses in 3 months) and regions with a response time greater than 6 minutes. The result yielded two undeserved fishnet grids. We identified these regions and created a 2000 meter buffer for each fishnet grid. Since these buffers intersected, we took the intersecting area and determined where EMS services are best placed in Cincinnati. Placing an EMS service within the intersecting buffer would allow for better use of city resources so that both regions can both be served within one location. It is important to note that both fishnet grids identified as having slow EMS delay times and a high risk of a heroin overdose are near hospitals and fire stations. We interpret this as that although there are nearby EMS services, the EMS services provided do not meet the current demand. Therefore, although resources already exist in the downtown area, we recommend that more EMS services be placed in the identified region to best limit heroin overdoses. Finally, we identified vacancies with this region where EMS services can potentially be placed. That said, Cincinnati does an excellent job overall in providing fast EMS response times.

Conclusion

In summary, predicting heroin overdoses is essential so that the municipality can best allocate resources to people who will benefit the most from a solved the heroin overdose crisis. We believe that our model can be an effective tool in helping to solve the heroin overdose crisis in Cincinnati. To run our model, we created a training set and a test set utilizing 2016 data. Unfortunately, data entry was very inconsistent across time, and we could not predict on larger temporal scales. For example, 2015 had 1/3 of the number of data points, and 2017 only had 100 data points. Instead, we decided to utilize June 6-September 12th, 2016 as the training set, and September 12th- December 31st as the test set. We began by engaging in feature engineering, where we aggregated each of our variables into a fishnet grid. We also utilized feature engineering by using the nearest neighbor function and engineering our own features, such as the CBD variable. In the exploratory analysis, it became clear that larger amounts of heroin overdoses often occur near downtown regions. Consequently, we decided to import features such as bus stops and traffic accidents into the model to help account for this clustering of heroin overdoses. In the exploratory analysis, the Moran’s I also revealed that significant clustering of heroin overdoses occur in the downtown of Cincinnati. Variables that we noticed having strong correlations with the count of overdoses in each fishnet include traffic, shootings, theft, assaults, burglaries, vandalism, central business district, and foreclosures. We ensured that each of the variables is independent of one another by creating a correlation plot. Finally, we found that joining neighborhoods made a significant difference in the model.

The model itself consisted of two fishnets; one fishnet as the training set and one fishnet as the test set. When cross-validating the data, we utilized Poisson regression because our model had a Poisson distribution. The predictions were calculated, utilizing both LOGO-CV and K-Fold Validation. We determined that the K-Fold regression yielded the better model. We believe this because it generalizes better across racial and poverty contexts. Additionally, there are lower mean average errors associated with our model when divided into folds. However, both models generalized well across different contexts, having mean average error values. When comparing our model to the kernel density, the mean average errors were comparable. Our model performed slightly better than the kernel density at the highest risk category. Although the kernel density model may be a more cost effective approach for a city, our model likely generalizes much better across different race and socioeconomic contexts. This is significant because these models are used to allocate resources. If the model underpredicts for a given race or socioeconomic class, those communities will be underserved if the model is put into production. Our Moran’s I also indicates that there is not any spatial autocorrelation in our errors. The Moran’s I of errors was approximately 0.

Finally, we analyze where services in Cincinnati should be placed. We accomplish this goal by looking at both EMS services and community/ rehab centers. For EMS services, we were looking for areas where we recommend the city to locate EMS services. Specifically, we looked for fishnet grid cells where EMS delay time was high, and risk predictions were high. We identified only two fishnet grid cells, indicating that Cincinnati is already doing an excellent job at providing EMS services to high-risk heroin overdose regions. Once our area is identified, we identified vacant lots that fall within our recommend region. A similar process was repeated to identify locations for the placement of rehab centers and addiction support services. We identified only one high-risk area that was underserved, meaning that Cinncinati is overall providing necessary services to high-risk areas. Although we identified vacant regions where we believe a rehab center should be placed, we recognize that this is a challenge in this location due to the current zoning laws.
